---
The Confluence Texts are the primary scholarly legacy of the Chromatic Circle—vast libraries
documenting every observed interaction between magical spell schools that Circle practitioners
could produce, test, and reproduce. Unlike the Axiomatic Schools' formal proofs, which were
organized by individual school, the Confluence Texts were organized by interaction type:
resonance effects, interference effects, amplification effects, cancellation effects, and the
complex multi-party effects that emerge when practitioners from different schools engage
simultaneously. This organizational structure was deliberate and controversial. The Axiomatic
Schools classified much of the Texts' content as unverifiable—not because Circle practitioners
documented incorrectly but because verification required multi-school simultaneous engagement
that single-school practitioners structurally could not perform. The Circle's response was
technically correct and institutionally ineffective: institutions controlling credential
recognition and research funding defined the scope of legitimate inquiry, and the Texts fell
outside that scope. During academic consolidation, the Confluent Theorists—the Circle faction
that maintained the full theoretical implications of the Texts—produced the Convergence Codices,
largely suppressed. The Texts survive in fragmented form across apprentice chains, each
preserving the sections most relevant to the elemental schools its practitioners specialized in.

flags MIDGAARD
---
Midgaard's Axiomatic institutions hold partial Confluence Text copies in restricted archives.
Suppression was content-selective: sections inconsistent with Axiomatic proof standards were
withheld and filed under restricted access. Continuity faction treats this as appropriate
management of unverified material. Reckoning faction notes it replicates the sealed-testimony
problem: the restricting institution has a stake in whether the content is treated as legitimate.
Current policy permits Sorcerer practitioners supervised access; copying is prohibited; notes
are reviewed before removal. The Convergence Codices—which vindicate the Texts' framework—are
available in full in Midgaard's civic library, a situation Axiomatic institutions cannot reverse
given the Codices' post-suppression vindication status.

flags KOWLOON
---
Kowloon's Jade Magistracy holds operational interest in the Confluence Texts' atmospheric
interaction sections. The Ash-and-Iron Decades stormbinder intervention—Grand Magi redirecting
ash-laden storm fronts using overlapping elemental disruption, the first documented large-scale
parallel elemental invocation—drew on Confluence Text methodology. Kowloon's emergency protocol
framework references this intervention as the benchmark for large-scale elemental crisis response.
The Jade Magistracy maintains a working copy of the atmospheric sections obtained through Grand
Magi channels rather than Axiomatic academic networks. Kowloon's copy contains stormbinder-era
annotations not present in any other known copy.

flags KIESS
---
Kiess treats the Confluence Texts as a case study in institutional authority functioning as
epistemological suppression: the Axiomatic Schools declared multi-school interaction effects
outside legitimate inquiry not because evidence was insufficient but because verification required
capabilities the Schools structurally lacked. Kiess maintains the most complete single-city
Confluence Text fragment collection accessible to independent researchers, assembled as part of
its anti-suppression scholarship program—the same program that documented Evermeet's participation
in the Spirebound Conclave apparatus.

flags RAKUEN
